---
import DocLayout from "../../../layouts/DocLayout.astro";
import Example from "../../../components/docs/Example.astro";
---

<DocLayout
  title="Getting started"
  eyebrow="Start here"
  description="Start from a brief, a source folder, or a creative skill. Let your agent create the OpenPress workspace, or run the CLI directly."
>
  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Prerequisites.</strong> Node.js 20+ with <code>npm</code> and <code>npx</code>.
    Chromium and <code>wrangler</code> are only needed when exporting PDF/images or deploying to Cloudflare.
  </div>

  <h2>1. Choose your start path</h2>

  <h3>Path A · AI-first: install skills, then ask the agent</h3>

  <p>
    Best for AI-first users, non-technical users, and opinionated formats. Install the OpenPress
    skill bundle first, then add any creative or domain skill that knows the publication style.
  </p>

  <Example title="Install skills" language="bash" code={`npx -y skills@latest add \\
  quan0715/open-press

# Optional creative/domain skill
npx -y skills@latest add \\
  quan0715/openpress-social-card-skill`} />

  <p>
    Restart the agent session after installation so the new skills are visible. Then ask the agent
    to initialize the workspace. The OpenPress skills should guide it to run the CLI, install the
    packages, copy or adapt skill-owned starter files, and verify the result.
  </p>

  <Example title="Prompt the agent" language="text" code={`我想做一份固定版面文件。請使用 OpenPress skills：
1. 確認 Node / npm / npx 可用
2. 用 @open-press/cli 初始化 workspace
3. 安裝需要的 @open-press packages
4. 套用合適的 skill starter 或範例
5. 跑 npm run build 驗證`} />

  <h3>Path B · CLI-first: run the commands yourself</h3>

  <p>
    Best for developers who already know the target folder, title, and workflow. The
    <code>npx</code> command downloads the CLI package; init creates the workspace and runs
    <code>npm install</code> by default.
  </p>

  <Example title="Create workspace" language="bash" code={`npx -y @open-press/cli@latest \\
  init my-paper \\
  --title "Transport models in dense networks"

cd my-paper`} />

  <Example title="If package install was skipped" language="bash" code={`npm install

# If skill sync failed
npm run openpress:skills`} />

  <p>
    Starter content comes from skills, not bundled packs. OpenPress initializes the document
    workspace; skills own intake, examples, starter files, and taste. See
    <a href="/docs/skills">Skills</a> for the ownership split.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Edit content</h2>

  <p>
    Everything you write lives under <code>press/</code>. Runtime internals live in
    <code>node_modules/@open-press/</code> after install; treat those packages as read-only.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><code>press/&lt;slug&gt;/press.tsx</code> — one Press Tree entry. <code>&lt;Press&gt;</code> props declare title / page / sources; children declare the page tree. See <a href="/docs/api/press">&lt;Press&gt;</a>.</li>
    <li><code>press/&lt;slug&gt;/chapters/**/*.mdx</code> — page prose, broken into chapters. Each chapter is one MDX file inside a folder; subfolders become document sections.</li>
    <li><code>press/&lt;slug&gt;/components/**/*.tsx</code> — Press-local React components.</li>
    <li><code>press/&lt;slug&gt;/theme/</code> and <code>press/shared/theme/</code> — CSS tokens, page surfaces, type scale, optional pattern utilities. See <a href="/docs/themes">Themes</a>.</li>
    <li><code>press/&lt;slug&gt;/media/</code> and <code>press/shared/media/</code> — images, vector assets. Synced into the public bundle on export.</li>
    <li><code>package.json</code> — the <code>"openpress.deploy"</code> field is where build-time deploy adapter settings live. See <a href="/docs/config">Workspace config</a>.</li>
  </ul>

  <Example title="Minimum press/report/press.tsx" language="tsx" code={`import { Press, Frame, mdxSource } from "@open-press/core";
import { Sections, Toc } from "@open-press/core/manuscript";

export default function ReportPress() {
  return (
    <Press
      slug="report"
      title="My document"
      page="a4"
      componentsDir="./components"
      mediaDir="./media"
      sources={[
        mdxSource({ id: "story", preset: "section-folders", root: "report/chapters" }),
      ]}
    >
      <Frame frameKey="cover" role="document.cover">
        <h1>My document</h1>
        {/* subtitle / organization / author all live in JSX */}
      </Frame>
      <Toc source="story" maxLevel={2} />
      <Sections source="story" />
    </Press>
  );
}`} />

  <h2>3. Live preview</h2>

<Example title="Start the workbench" language="bash" code={`npm run dev
# → http://127.0.0.1:5173/workspace`} />

  <p>
    The workbench reloads CSS, tokens, and React chrome on save. MDX content updates flow through
    the engine's source watcher. The <code>/workspace</code> route opens the project gallery, and
    each document opens at <code>/&lt;press-slug&gt;/preview</code> with the workbench shell
    (inspector, source-edit endpoint, comment markers).
  </p>

  <h2>4. Build + verify</h2>

  <Example title="Production build" language="bash" code={`npm run build         # validates + renders dist-react/
npm run preview       # serve dist-react/ as a static site
npm run openpress:pdf # optional: generate PDF locally`} />

  <p>
    <code>build</code> chains structural validation, MDX → React export, and Vite production build.
    If validation fails the build aborts before Vite runs, so a green build means the document
    shape is consistent. See <a href="/docs/cli/lifecycle">CLI · Lifecycle</a> for what each step
    does.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Deploy</h2>

  <p>
    OpenPress requires explicit confirmation for any deploy — there is no silent publish. Configure
    the adapter under the <code>"openpress.deploy"</code> field in the workspace
    <code>package.json</code>, then:
  </p>

  <Example title="Deploy to Cloudflare Pages" language="bash" code={`npm run openpress:deploy:dry-run        # preview the steps
npm run openpress:deploy -- --confirm   # publish`} />

  <p>
    The deploy command builds, generates a PDF stage artifact, writes <code>deploy.json</code>
    metadata, and hands off to the configured adapter. If a host-specific adapter is not
    implemented, use the generated build output directly and keep the publish step outside
    OpenPress.
  </p>

  <h2>What to read next</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><a href="/docs/product-boundary">Work with Agent</a> — how agents should initialize, edit, verify, and stop at boundaries.</li>
    <li><a href="/docs/themes">Themes</a> — the <code>press/&lt;slug&gt;/theme/</code> and <code>press/shared/theme/</code> contract.</li>
    <li><a href="/docs/api/press">Components → Press</a> — the Press Tree primitives.</li>
    <li><a href="/docs/comments">Comment markers</a> — the inline-review workflow.</li>
    <li><a href="/docs/cli">CLI</a> — full command reference (three tiers).</li>
  </ul>
</DocLayout>
